---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { getPost } from '../../data/posts';
import { engageHref, projects, withBase } from '../../site.config';

const post = getPost('zero-trust-gitops-gke-connect')!;
const siteOrigin = Astro.site?.origin ?? 'https://sollabs.tech';
const structuredData = [
  {
    '@type': 'BlogPosting',
    headline: post.title,
    datePublished: post.date,
    description: post.description,
    author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Sol Labs' },
    publisher: { '@id': `${siteOrigin}/#organization` },
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title={`${post.title} · Sol Labs`}
  description={post.description}
  current="blog"
  ogType="article"
  publishedTime={post.date}
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <article class="page-wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <p class="meta">{post.date} · {post.icp}</p>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>
        <strong>TL;DR:</strong> Zero Trust on GKE means the Kubernetes API is not a wide-open network
        hop. Centralize Argo CD, reach private clusters through GKE Connect, and authenticate every
        sync with identity — not long-lived kubeconfigs on a jump box.
      </p>

      <h2>GCP DevSecOps — Zero Trust delivery, not bolted-on scans</h2>
      <p>
        Security that ships with the platform beats security that arrives before an audit. The useful
        pattern is the same one successful GCP DevSecOps practices describe: least-privilege IAM from
        day one, CI/CD that authenticates without service-account keys, Terraform with policy gates,
        and GKE hardened before workloads land — not a patchwork of reviews after the fact.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sol Labs implements that path hands-on. The same architecture is built into
        <a href={projects.kanto.href}>Kanto</a>: Zero Trust identity for cluster access, a
        centralized Argo CD control plane, and GKE Connect so GitOps talks to private cluster APIs
        without punching holes in the network.
      </p>

      <h2>The problem most teams face</h2>
      <p>
        Most GCP environments do not have a missing-scanner problem. They have a security-debt
        problem — controls that were never designed in, now fragile and expensive to retrofit:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          IAM grew organically. Project-level bindings and convenience service accounts make “who can
          do what” hard to explain to an auditor.
        </li>
        <li>
          Service-account keys and long-lived kubeconfigs live in CI secrets, laptops, and ConfigMaps.
        </li>
        <li>
          Pipelines and GitOps agents hold broader permissions than any single job needs — every
          release becomes a potential misconfiguration vector.
        </li>
        <li>
          Private GKE was enabled, but the control plane is still reached by brittle bastion paths or
          broad authorized networks instead of identity-aware access.
        </li>
        <li>
          Policies exist in docs; the platform does not enforce them on every sync.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The result is a platform that works — and is one misconfiguration away from a serious incident.
      </p>

      <h2>What we typically put in place</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Zero Trust identity for cluster and GCP access.</strong> No implicit trust between
          humans, CI, and workloads. Workload Identity Federation where GCP APIs are called; scoped
          identities for every sync path.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Centralized Argo CD.</strong> One GitOps control plane for the fleet — SSO,
          least-privilege RBAC, and production sync gates — instead of a snowflake Argo in every
          cluster that nobody can audit the same way twice.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>GKE Connect for Zero Trust Kubernetes API access.</strong> Private clusters stay
          private. Centralized Argo CD reaches the API through Connect membership, so delivery does
          not depend on a flat network path or a standing kubeconfig on a bastion.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Least-privilege IAM and key elimination.</strong> Scope service accounts to
          workloads; replace static keys with federation for GKE, GitHub Actions, and Cloud Build.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Policy at deploy time.</strong> Admission controls and infrastructure policy checks
          before apply/sync — so the platform enforces the baseline instead of hoping people remember
          it.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>DevSecOps in practice: Connect + centralized Argo CD</h2>
      <p>
        The pattern that matters for multi-cluster GCP teams:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Clusters are private; the Kubernetes API is not on the public internet.</li>
        <li>Clusters register to a fleet via GKE Connect / Anthos Connect membership.</li>
        <li>
          A centralized Argo CD instance authenticates to each cluster’s API through that Connect
          path — identity-bound, auditable, without opening broad network trust to the control plane.
        </li>
        <li>
          Desired state lives in Git. Humans approve. Sync events and Git history become the change
          evidence trail — not screenshots from a last-minute scramble.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        That is the Zero Trust delivery spine Kanto is built around: GitOps that can reach private
        GKE without abandoning least privilege.
      </p>

      <h2>What a secure platform architecture looks like</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Workload Identity (and federation) for GCP authentication — no SA key files in the path</li>
        <li>Private GKE nodes; restricted control-plane access</li>
        <li>Centralized Argo CD with Connect-backed cluster registration</li>
        <li>Namespace isolation, Pod Security baselines, and deploy-time policy</li>
        <li>Centralized audit logs and retention tuned to how you actually operate</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Who this is for</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Teams on production GKE with security debt (keys, over-broad IAM, fragile GitOps)</li>
        <li>Orgs under enterprise or compliance pressure that need structural controls, not binders</li>
        <li>Platform teams consolidating many clusters onto one operable GitOps control plane</li>
        <li>Migrations onto GCP where the security model must be cloud-native from the start</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        This is not a fit for single-VM hosting or teams without a delivery pipeline. If you need the
        broader platform lane first, start with
        <a href={withBase('/services/gke-soc2-readiness/')}>production GKE and GitOps</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Next step</h2>
      <p>
        Want security designed into the delivery path — not bolted on before a deal? We start with a
        short architecture conversation: current posture, highest-risk gaps, and what Zero Trust
        GitOps looks like on your fleet. Proof lives in
        <a href={projects.kanto.href}>Kanto</a>.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a
          class="btn btn--primary"
          href={engageHref}
          data-analytics-event="primary_cta_click"
          data-analytics-prop-location="article_zero_trust_gitops"
        >
          Let's Talk
        </a>
        {' '}
        <a class="btn btn--secondary" href={withBase('/services/gke-soc2-readiness/')}>GKE SOC 2 Readiness</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
